[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring H2 and metadata**\n\nI'm considering whether H2 has GraalVM reachability metadata, possibly central metadata. Current tests might include a metadata repo and dependencies. H2 is widely used. Liquibase probably utilizes service loaders and dynamic reflection with existing metadata. I'm wondering if artifact forge will generate metadata only for Spring Boot classes and if dependencies will filter out user code. \n\nI need to write Java adhering to Checkstyle rules, focusing on class names, package names, and imports. I'll also consider licensing and temporary XML string escaping. Lastly, I should check for potential deprecations in APIs related to Liquibase, particularly SpringLiquibase.setLabels and setContexts.\n\n**Creating a unique DB name**\n\nI'm thinking about how to handle the public API belonging to the dependency, which seems fine. I need to create a unique database name for each temporary instance. Using an Atomic reference or a UUID could work well. When using a native image, a random approach is acceptable. I can construct the H2 URL like this: `jdbc:h2:mem:` plus a UUID, then append `;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1;DATABASE_TO_UPPER=false`. This should set everything up correctly!\n\n**Evaluating connection details testing**\n\nI'm thinking about asserting non-nullity, but it doesn't seem useful since there's only a public constructor. A good test could be `autoConfigurationTypesCanBeInstantiated` to check if new instances can be created. I could also test the default method in `LiquibaseConnectionDetails`, making sure the driver class name is null. Additionally, I should verify that all fields are bound correctly, which means I'd need to build on and edit my tests accordingly.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f5d8b103a150f48016a3ef5f8826c8194ae5ad04e96190008\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqPvYMDW7m4MeO641